      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Many are in awe that any new Dodge Vipers are still out there. Some dealers have apparently put a few of the snakes in cold storage since they knew the end was nigh. At a time when we’re served up Corvettes with automatic transmissions and some weird strip of buttons on the center stack, these heroes are providing something far rawer and more visceral that speaks to our baser instincts. Give us a stick shift or give us death, we say!",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "src": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2020/10/Motorious--26.jpg",
        "width": 1920,
        "height": 1080,
        "caption": "photo credit: Fiat Chrysler Automobiles"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Not everyone can handle a real sports car that doesn’t babysit the driver. That’s what we attribute the death of the Dodge Viper to, and it’s sad. We hope Fiat Chrysler realizes there’s still a place in this world for the Viper, a true American sports car that speaks to the very soul of enthusiasts. Even in death it’s rescuing us, so maybe it’ll come back just like zombie Superman, only more evil.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
